 Dutch|Germans from Pennsylvania]] who moved to Baltimore. It has a bilingual congregation that provides sermons in both [[German language|German]] and [[English language|English]]. In 1762 the congregation built its first church on Fish Street (later East Fayette Street). By 1773, a new church constitution had replaced the church's earlier core document,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hofmann|first1=Julius|title=A History of Zion Church of the City of Baltimore, 1755-1897|date=October 15, 1905|publisher=C.W. Schneidereith & Sons|location=Baltimore|page=20|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_bnzTAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> and eventually, the 1762 structure was also replaced by a bigger building, the current Zion Church on North Gay Street, erected from 1807 to 1808 in a Gothic style.<ref name=\"mht_ihp\">{{cite web|url=https://mht.maryland.gov/secure/medusa/PDF/NR_PDFs/NR-1523.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Zion Lutheran Church|date=August 2010|accessdate=2016-03-01 |author=Susan Detherage|publisher=Maryland Historical Trust}}</ref>  An additional expansion of the church to the west along East Lexington Street to North Holliday Street composed of an \"Adlersaal\" (Parish House), bell tower, parsonage and an enclosed garden designed of Hanseatic North German architecture was constructed under Rev. Julius K. Hoffman in 1912-1913.  In the late 1920s, the entire block south of the church was razed to form a monumental square (known as [[War Memorial Plaza]] or, less frequently, as \"City Hall Plaza\") opposite the [[Baltimore City Hall]] of 1875 on the western side and construction at the eastern end of the War Memorial Building with an auditorium, historical exhibit area and veterans organizations offices.  On the south side of the church buildings facing the plaza, a new headquarters for the [[Baltimore City Fire Department]] was constructed in a Georgian-Federal style complementing the original Zion Church around the corner.\n\nGerman-language sermons have been provided for over 250 years at Zion Church, the only church left in Maryland still holding weekly German-language services. The church participates in the annual Maryland German Festival and is a member of the German-American Citizens Association of Maryland. The German community has ties to Henry Stiegel<ref>https://jefpat.maryland.gov/Pages/mac-lab/curators-choice/2015-curators-choice/2015-10-the-mystery-of-stiegel-type-glassware.aspx</ref>.  \n\nZion Church was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/listings/20120106.htm |title=Zion Lutheran Church |publisher=[[National Park Service]] |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref>\n\n==People==\n\nThe composer [[George Frederick Boyle]] was married at the church.\n\n[[Image:ZionBaltoWall.JPG|thumb|A piece of the Berlin Wall at Zion Church, Baltimore, MD. The inscription reads: \"This piece of the Berlin Wall stood near Lichterfelde until broken by the sledgehammer of Mr. Rick DeLisle on November 11, 1989, at 6:50 am. Donated by WMIX 106.5 FM Baltimore and dedicated to those who crossed and those who gave their lives in the attempt.]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of the Germans in Baltimore]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Central Baltimore]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://zionbaltimore.org/ Zion Church] official website\n*{{MHT url|id=1605|title=Zion Lutheran Church, Baltimore City}}, including undated photo, at Maryland Historical Trust\n*[http://www.zionbaltimore.org/index.htm Official website of the church]\n*[http://homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~zimzip/balto/churches3.htm Church history from RootsWeb]\n*[http://baltimore.about.com/od/artsentertaiment/ig/Heritage-Walk-Tour/Zion-Lutheran-Church-.htm Church information on About.com]\n*[http://monumentcity.net/2010/01/02/zion-lutheran-church-baltimore/ Church history from Monument City blog]\n*[http://www.germanmarylan